 definitely not, as this article claims,\nthe original!) And then the 1964 law happened, setting up a bunch of\nbureaucracy to help things along, and all that progress that black Americans\nwere making suddenly hit a hard wall. By the 1980s, with the \"help\" of a\nlethal combination of bad policy and cocaine, they were \"advancing\" backwards,\ngiving up decades of real progress.Post-1964 Civil Rights Law Is Bad, because\nnot only does it create all of the devastating knock-on effects described by\nHanania in his book, *it does so while also doing harm to its own stated goals\nrather than advancing them!*Expand full commentReply (4)Share  \n---  \n  \nScott Alexander45 mins agoAuthorIn terms of Asians, I think most Asians I know\nthink of themselves as Asian to some degree. Obviously the Chinese and\nJapanese don't get along, but neither do Russians and Ukrainians and they\nstill (at least in America) share a certain identity as \"white\".Expand full\ncommentReply (1)Share  \n---  \n  \nTGGP28 mins agoThe salience of \"white\" is not a constant over time. It's not\ntrue that \"The Irish Became White\", as they were always so legally, but intra-\nracial inter-ethnic differences were more salient in the US long ago.Expand\nfull commentReply (1)Share  \n---  \n  \nScott Alexander24 mins agoAuthorHow is this different from \"Asian\"?Expand full\ncommentReply (1)Share  \n---  \n  \nTGGP17 mins agoI don't think South Asians previously lumped themselves\ntogether with East Asians. On the other hand, Middle Easterners are legally\nconsidered white, and previously they & Europeans wouldn't lump themselves\ntogether, and now Middle Easterners are politically mobilizing to get a\nseparate category.Expand full commentReplyShare  \n---  \n  \ncarateca45 mins agoMy favorite example of Asian \"solidarity\" was a kerfuffle\nabout a Japanese cultural exhibit in Boston where visitors could try on\nkimonos. It was shut down as anti-Asian by a _Chinese_ activist against the\nwill of t